									<p>India Office stamped foliation. </p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>Catchwords. </p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Slightly worm-eaten. Damp-stained. Some loose leaves. Without
										binding, encased in a wrapper. </p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1 3" writtenLines="15">
									<p>15 lines per page. </p>
									<p>The verse is arranged either in 2 columns or in 3 with 2
										columns written diagonally either side of a central vertical
										line. </p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc>
							<summary/>
							<handNote medium="ink">
								<p>Nastaʻlīq, written in black ink. </p>
							</handNote>
						</handDesc>
						<decoDesc>
							<decoNote>Written on coloured paper. </decoNote>
						</decoDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Folio 1r includes verses in Urdu written directly under the seal of
								Muḥammad Ṣadr al-Dīn dated 1235 (1819/20) who may possibly be
								identified with <persName role="asn" key="viaf_208843048">Muḥammad
									Ṣadr al-Dīn Āzurdah</persName> (1798-1868), the poet and
									<foreign xml:lang="fa">Sadr Amin</foreign> of Delhi whose
								library was confiscated and auctioned by the Delhi Prize Agents
								after the rebellion of 1857. </p>
						</additions>
						<sealDesc>
							<seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
								<p>Black rectangular seal of <persName role="fmo" key="person_f8448">Muḥammad
										Ṣadr al-Dīn </persName>, dated 1235 AH (1819-20 CE) (f. 1r).</p>
							</seal>
							<seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
								<p>Black Government of India Delhi MSS oval stamp (ff. 1r, 81v).</p>
							</seal>
						</sealDesc>
						<accMat>
							<p>Wrapper: East India Company Regulation dated 1793. </p>
						</accMat>
					</physDesc>
					<history>
						<origin calendar="Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1799">4 Muḥarram regnal year 6 of unspecified
							reign. Probably 18th century; <origPlace>India</origPlace>
